                div(class="row row-flex")
                    p When speaking about possessions in English, such as the property of someone or the qualities of a person or object we use an “S” with an apostrophe (‘) to show ownership or possession.
                    div(class="col xs12 md6 mb30"): div(class="xs12 md11 col-center")
                        h6 Look at the examples below
                        div(class="c-cardBlue")
                            div(class="c-cardBlueContent u-textColor_1")
                                ul.lh25
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Camilo’s new diet includes a lot of meat.
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Francine’s new exercise routine burns a lot of calories.
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Angie’s test results were all normal.
                    |
                    div(class="col xs12 md6 mb30"): div(class="xs12 md11 col-center")
                        h6 When a noun is in the plural form we usually place the apostrophe outside of the “s”
                        div(class="c-cardBlue")
                            div(class="c-cardBlueContent u-textColor_1")
                                ul.lh25
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Singular: The cat’s favorite food is canned tuna.
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Plural: The cats’ favorite food is canned tuna.
                    |
                    div(class="col xs12 md6 mb30"): div(class="xs12 md11 col-center")
                        h6 In Spanish, it is customary to use “of.” Although “of” is very common in Spanish, in English it is not.
                        p Here are some cases where “of” can be used:
                        div(class="c-cardBlue")
                            div(class="c-cardBlueContent u-textColor_1")
                                ul.lh25
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  Colombia’s culture is very interesting.
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  The culture of Colombia is very interesting.
                    |
                    div(class="col xs12 md6 mb30"): div(class="xs12 md11 col-center")
                        h6 Also, we use “of” when something is a part of another rather than a possession
                        div(class="c-cardBlue")
                            div(class="c-cardBlueContent u-textColor_1")
                                ul.lh25
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  The color of the pants is blue
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  The ceiling of my room is high.
                                    li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •]  The walls of the apartment are thin.
                div(class="row")
                    div(class="xs12 col-center")
                        p Let’s look at the following rare exceptions to the rule when using abbreviations, letters, or words that are not normally nouns are used as nouns.
                        ul
                            li  #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Tania received two A’s and three B’s.
                            li  #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The hospital hired three M.D.’s and two D.O.’s.
                            li  #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Do you have more yes’s than no’s?
                            li  #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Yeses and noes is also use in the last example.

                        h6 Write the plural for of the following examples.

                        table(class="c-table-estilo_tres")
                            thead
                                tr
                                    th Singular
                                    th Plural
                            tbody
                                tr
                                    td 2 and 3
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir row" )
                                tr
                                    td DUI
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir row" )
                                tr
                                    td ABC
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir row" )
            |
            div(class="row u-animationFadeDown" ng-show="s_actividad == 2")
                div(class="col xs12 md10 col-center")
                    p The possessive of a plural noun is formed by adding only an apostrophe when the noun ends in s, and by adding both an apostrophe and s when it ends in a letter other than s.
                    .col.xs12.md6
                        ul.lh25
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Excessive lawyers’ fees.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Children’s backpacks.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The twins’ grandparents.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The student teachers’ counselor.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The Salas’ vacation villa.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The girls’ softball team.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The alumni’s fundraising.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] An editor with at least ten years’ experience
                    |
                    .col.xs12.md6
                        h6 Complete the table by writing the possessive form of the following nouns.
                        table(class="c-table-estilo_tres m-a")
                            thead
                                tr
                                    th Plural form
                                    th Possessive form
                            tbody
                                tr
                                    td Bacteria
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                                tr
                                    td Syllabi
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                                tr
                                    td Bosses
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                                tr
                                    td Managers
                                    td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                div(class="col xs12 md10 col-center")
                        h5 Exceptions to the general rule
                        .col.xs12.md10
                            p Use only an apostrophe for places or names that are singular but have a final word in plural form and ending with an s.
                            ul.lh25
                                li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Beverly Hills’ former mayor.
                                li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] The United States’ lingering debt problem
                                li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Cellar Systems’ CEO.
                            h6 Complete the table with the possessive form of the following nouns.
                            table(class="c-table-estilo_tres m-a")
                                thead
                                    tr
                                        th Noun
                                        th Possessive form
                                tbody
                                    tr
                                        td The United Emirates
                                        td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                                    tr
                                        td Caracas
                                        td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
                                    tr
                                        td Telecoms
                                        td: input(type="text" class="c-input js-escribir" )
            |
            div(class="row u-animationFadeDown" ng-show="s_actividad == 3")
                .row-flex.justify-between.align-items-center
                    .col.xs12.md6
                        h6 Nouns that end in an s sound take only an apostrophe when they are followed by sake.
                        ul.lh25
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] For goodness’ sake.
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] For conscience’ sake.
                        h6 A proper noun that is already in possessive form is left as is.
                        ul.lh25
                            li #[strong.u-textColor_4 •] Chilly’s menu was recently changed.

                        h6 Complete the table with the possessive from the first column.

                        table(class="c-table-estilo_tres m-a")
                            thead
